You're comparing apples to oranges there, with my quote.<br>
<br>
I was doing a discursive analysis, trying to find the underlying cultural ideologies influencing your claims that Shintou's opinions were comparable to racism.  Even in your own post, you question whether that might be a stretch (and then discount that with &quot;I doubt it&quot;).  I was not trying to attack, or even question, your character, but trying to analyze at how you arrived at that particular conclusion (a conclusion I think is dubious, but you know that).<br>
<br>
Rhetorically speaking, saying someone is &quot;intolerant&quot; is an attempt to shut down the conversation.  You may say it's &quot;calling a spade a spade&quot;, but rhetorically, it's meant to cast the opposition as unreasonable and yourself as imminently reasonable.  There is no rational response to it beyond &quot;No, I'm not intolerant&quot;; it derails discussion of issues into discussion of character.<br>
<br>
While it's not as scurulous as calling someone the various other names that were flung around, it's still in the category of &quot;personal attack&quot;.<br>
